::Five Future-Proofing Strategies::According to Clark and Chamorro-Premuzic's HBR article, which of the following is NOT one of the five strategies to future-proof your career in the age of AI?{
~Avoid predictability #Incorrect. 'Avoid predictability' IS one of the five strategies—seeking roles that require contextual judgment rather than routine tasks.
=Focus exclusively on technical skills #Correct! 'Focus exclusively on technical skills' is NOT a recommended strategy. The framework emphasizes balancing technical literacy with soft skills.
~Build genuine human relationships #Incorrect. 'Build genuine human relationships' IS one of the five strategies—networking and trust-building that AI cannot replicate.
~Develop soft skills #Incorrect. 'Develop soft skills' IS one of the five strategies—communication, empathy, creativity, and emotional intelligence become MORE valuable as technical work automates.
####This is a common misconception worth addressing\: many students assume that in a tech-driven future, only technical skills matter. The opposite is true. As routine technical work gets automated, what remains is inherently more complex, more human-centered, and requires <b>judgment, creativity, empathy, and communication</b>. Your career strategy should develop technical literacy AND human skills, not technical skills exclusively.}

::Five Future-Proofing Strategies::The future-proofing strategy "Avoid Predictability" is based on which core principle?{
~Unpredictable work schedules help build resilience #Incorrect. This misinterprets the strategy. 'Avoid Predictability' refers to the nature of work tasks, not scheduling unpredictability.
=If a job can be reduced to predictable, rules-based steps, it can be automated #Correct! 'Avoid Predictability' means if work is predictable and rules-based, it's automatable. Seek roles requiring contextual judgment.
~Career planning should avoid setting concrete goals #Incorrect. The strategy is about the predictability of work tasks themselves, not about avoiding goal-setting (which is actually important for career planning).
~Workers should frequently change jobs to avoid boredom #Incorrect. The strategy is about seeking work involving novelty and judgment within roles, not about job-hopping.
####Apply this principle when evaluating career paths and job opportunities. Ask yourself\: "Could the core tasks of this role be reduced to a set of predictable steps?" If yes, that role faces high automation risk. Seek roles where you're solving novel problems, making judgment calls in ambiguous situations, or creating something new. For example, <b>data entry is predictable; data interpretation requiring business context is not</b>. Position yourself accordingly.}

::Five Future-Proofing Strategies::Why does the strategy "Build Genuine Human Relationships" become MORE important in the AI era rather than less?{
~AI has eliminated the need for technical skills, making relationships the only differentiator #Incorrect. Technical skills still matter. The point is that relationships become a key differentiator IN ADDITION TO technical capabilities.
~Networking events are now held virtually, making them easier to attend #Incorrect. The format of networking is not the core reason. The strategy emphasizes that human decision-making remains based on trust and relationships.
=Humans make final decisions based on trust and relationships, which AI cannot replicate #Correct! Relationship-building matters more because humans make decisions based on trust and relationships—something AI cannot replicate.
~Relationship-building is easier than developing technical skills #Incorrect. The strategy is based on the irreplaceability of human relationships, not on ease of development.
####Your <b>mentorship program</b> is a structured opportunity to practice professional relationship-building. Approach it strategically\: prepare thoughtfully for meetings, follow through on mentor advice, maintain contact beyond minimum requirements. The field trip to MISA and guest speaker session are networking opportunities—connect with people on LinkedIn afterward, send thank-you messages, request informational interviews. These relationship-building actions compound over your career and often matter more than perfect grades.}

::Five Future-Proofing Strategies::The strategy "Aim for Originality" may be particularly challenging for Vietnamese students because\:{
~Vietnamese students lack creativity compared to other nationalities #Incorrect. This is a harmful stereotype. Vietnamese students have equal creative potential; the challenge is educational system emphasis, not innate ability.
=Vietnamese education traditionally emphasizes mastering established knowledge over innovation #Correct! Vietnamese education traditionally emphasizes mastering established knowledge and following best practices, making innovation feel less comfortable—but this is developable.
~Original thinking is not valued in Vietnamese business culture #Incorrect. Vietnamese business increasingly values innovation and entrepreneurship. The challenge is educational preparation, not cultural values.
~Vietnamese language structure makes original thinking impossible #Incorrect. Language does not limit original thinking. The challenge is educational system emphasis on mastery over innovation.
####If you rated yourself low on "originality" in your tutorial self-assessment, recognize this is common and addressable. Start small\: in class discussions, propose one unconventional idea. In group projects, suggest an approach that hasn't been tried before. Read case studies of successful Vietnamese entrepreneurs. Week 10's focus on <b>entrepreneurial mindset</b> and the guest speaker session will provide additional exposure to innovative thinking. Remember\: originality doesn't mean reckless risk-taking—it means thoughtfully questioning assumptions and proposing new approaches.}

::Human-AI Collaboration::Which of the following is a key capability for effective human-AI collaboration according to Week 1 content?{
~Using AI to replace all human thinking and judgment #Incorrect. Effective collaboration requires maintaining human judgment, not replacing it. AI supports human thinking; it doesn't replace it.
~Avoiding AI tools entirely to preserve human jobs #Incorrect. Avoiding AI is not a viable strategy. The goal is to learn how to work WITH AI effectively, not avoid it.
=Context engineering—crafting effective prompts and queries for AI tools #Correct! Context engineering—the ability to craft effective prompts and queries—is a key human-AI collaboration skill that will be explored in Week 2.
~Memorizing AI-generated outputs without evaluation #Incorrect. Blindly accepting AI outputs is dangerous. Effective collaboration requires critical evaluation of AI outputs, not memorization.
####Human-AI collaboration is not about humans OR AI—it's about humans AND AI working together strategically. You provide contextual understanding, judgment, creativity, and ethical guidance. AI provides processing speed, pattern recognition, and content generation. <b>The most valuable workers won't be those who ignore AI or those who blindly trust it, but those who leverage AI while maintaining critical judgment.</b> Before Week 2, experiment with an AI tool as assigned—practice crafting clear prompts and critically evaluating outputs.}

::Human-AI Collaboration::When the lecture discusses developing "critical evaluation" skills for AI outputs, what does this mean in practice?{
~Criticizing AI tools in social media posts #Incorrect. 'Critical evaluation' means analytical assessment of outputs, not public criticism or complaining about AI tools.
=Knowing when to trust AI output and when to question or verify it #Correct! Critical evaluation means knowing when to trust AI output and when to question or verify it—applying human judgment to AI-generated content.
~Avoiding AI tools because they are unreliable #Incorrect. The solution is not avoidance but developing judgment about when AI is reliable and when it requires human verification.
~Using only the most expensive AI tools #Incorrect. Critical evaluation is about your analytical skills, not about which tools cost more money. Even expensive tools require human judgment.
####This skill will be essential throughout your career. As AI tools become ubiquitous in the workplace, employers will value workers who can leverage AI for productivity while catching errors and adding human judgment. In your coursework, when you use AI tools for assignments, don't just copy outputs—verify facts, evaluate quality, and add your own analysis. This practice develops the <b>complementary thinking</b> that makes human-AI collaboration effective rather than producing low-quality "workslop" (mediocre AI-generated content we'll discuss in Week 2).}
